<h1>📋 RS001 Week 3 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Lists and Choices · <strong>Course:</strong> Text Adventure (Python) · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you think about the <strong>list</strong> — one box that holds many values. You pull a value out by its <strong>index</strong>: the first item is <code>[0]</code>, the second is <code>[1]</code>, the third is <code>[2]</code>. On this sheet you read code, predict it, fix it on paper, and explain the code you wrote in today's lesson.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>list</strong>, <strong>index</strong>, <strong>first</strong>, <strong>inventory</strong>, <strong>value</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<pre><code class="language-python">weapons = [&quot;sword&quot;, &quot;bow&quot;, &quot;wand&quot;]
game.say(f&quot;You can choose: {weapons[0]}, {weapons[1]}, {weapons[2]}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Run it in your head — do not type it. Write what you think the screen will show.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">paths = [&quot;left&quot;, &quot;middle&quot;, &quot;right&quot;]
game.say(paths[1])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Which word appears? (Careful — counting starts at 0.)</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">enemies = [&quot;goblin&quot;, &quot;orc&quot;, &quot;dragon&quot;]
enemy_hp = [10, 25, 100]
game.say(f&quot;{enemies[2]} has {enemy_hp[2]} HP&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The two lists share the same index. What sentence is printed?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">items = [&quot;map&quot;, &quot;key&quot;, &quot;torch&quot;]
game.say(items[3])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The list has 3 items but the code asks for <code>[3]</code>. What goes wrong?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, fix it on paper, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This should print the <strong>first</strong> weapon in the list. Right now it prints the second one.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">weapons = [&quot;sword&quot;, &quot;bow&quot;, &quot;wand&quot;]
game.say(f&quot;Your first weapon: {weapons[1]}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the first item is not <code>[1]</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should show all three paths as a numbered menu. Right now every line shows the <strong>same</strong> path.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">paths = [&quot;cave&quot;, &quot;river&quot;, &quot;field&quot;]
game.say(f&quot;1: {paths[0]}&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;2: {paths[0]}&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;3: {paths[0]}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> lines 2 and 3 should use a different index.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The enemy name and its HP should belong to the <strong>same</strong> enemy. Right now the name is the goblin but the HP is the dragon's.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">enemy_names = [&quot;goblin&quot;, &quot;orc&quot;, &quot;dragon&quot;]
enemy_hp = [10, 25, 100]
game.say(f&quot;A {enemy_names[0]} appears! HP: {enemy_hp[2]}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the same enemy lives at the same index in both lists.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
